    {
      "text": "A 35-year-old woman has a history of nausea and vomiting, especially during her journeys. Which of the following would be the most appropriate drug for this patient to prevent the same during her next journey?",
      "choices": [
        {
          "id": 0,
          "text": "Fexofenadine"
        },
        {
          "id": 1,
          "text": "Hyoscine"
        },
        {
          "id": 2,
          "text": "Ondansetron"
        },
        {
          "id": 3,
          "text": "Metoclopramide"
        }
      ],
      "correct_choice_id": 1,
      "solution": "<p><strong>Correct answer: B) Hyoscine</strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>Explanation: </strong></p>\n\n<p>The above scenario is suggestive of motion sickness, and the drug of choice for the same is <strong>hyoscine/ scopolamine, </strong>which is an <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"9b4dbbb3321692777181e6fe172b88\">anticholinergic</span> (M1 <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"9e4959f6f316927771978bb152d440\">receptor</span> antagonist)</p>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<p><strong>Mechanism of action of anticholinergics and <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"4b296ae29b16927771815960a008db\">antihistaminic</span> drugs :</strong></p>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<ul>\n\t<li>M1 <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"9e4959f6f316927771978bb152d440\">receptor</span> and H1 receptors are present in the <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"a1b8deb0fe1692777190df5ce46525\">inner ear</span> <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"7732c8e49d169277719171da17de32\">labyrinth</span> and they get activated when there is movement (during journeys) in the semi-circular <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"371930068716927771839cba840631\">canal</span> ➞ <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"dddc752e1716927771807f985bb8bb\">activate</span> the <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"e8b3c606051692777201faf2a1a357\">vestibular</span> nerve ➞ stimulates CTZ in the brain ➞ <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"9a8412e39e1692777193c550a5dbb4\">nausea</span> and vomiting.</li>\n\t<li>M1 and H1 <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"9e4959f6f316927771978bb152d440\">receptor</span> blockers block this effect ➞ ⬇ <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"7f3792072b1692777199fd8e2c4f59\">stimulation</span> of the CTZ</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><br />\n </p>\n\n<p style=\"text-align:center\"><img alt=\"\" data-author=\"\" data-hash=\"\" data-license=\"\" data-source=\"\" data-tags=\"\" height=\"530\" src=\"https://image.prepladder.com/content/RA9ZjusfMQyXV2pM9PWJ1724071903.jpg\" width=\"530\" /></p>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<p><strong>DRUGS USED FOR <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"93772348231692777192fbdc055f11\">MOTION SICKNESS</span> :</strong></p>\n\n<ul>\n\t<li><strong>Anticholinergics : </strong>Scopolamine\n\n\t<ul>\n\t\t<li>Used as a <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"48982b740216927772004a198271cd\">transdermal</span> patch.</li>\n\t\t<li>Use 4 to 5 hours before travel.  </li>\n\t</ul>\n\t</li>\n\t<li><strong>Antihistamines : </strong>Diphenhydramine, Promethazine, and Cyclizine.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<p> </p>",
