    {
      "text": "A 70-year-old man with Parkinson's disease has recently started treatment with levodopa. He reports experiencing significant nausea and vomiting since beginning the medication. Which of the following antiemetics is appropriate for this patient’s condition?",
      "choices": [
        {
          "id": 0,
          "text": "Metoclopramide"
        },
        {
          "id": 1,
          "text": "Prochlorperazine"
        },
        {
          "id": 2,
          "text": "Chlorpromazine"
        },
        {
          "id": 3,
          "text": "Domperidone"
        }
      ],
      "correct_choice_id": 3,
      "solution": "<p><strong>Correct answer: D) Domperidone</strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>Explanation: </strong></p>\n\n<p>The above scenario suggests levodopa-induced <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"9a8412e39e1692777193c550a5dbb4\">nausea</span> and vomiting, and the drug of choice for the same is domperidone, which is a <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"9194a239ed1692777186bfe41c0e87\">dopamine</span> <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"9e4959f6f316927771978bb152d440\">receptor</span> (D2) antagonist.</p>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<p><strong>D2 <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"9e4959f6f316927771978bb152d440\">receptor</span> antagonists :</strong></p>\n\n<ul>\n\t<li><strong>Domperidone : </strong>\n\n\t<ul>\n\t\t<li>Treats levodopa-induced <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"9a8412e39e1692777193c550a5dbb4\">nausea</span> and vomiting.</li>\n\t\t<li>It<strong> does not cross </strong>the <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"d89cb634601692777183adec401a59\">blood-brain barrier</span> (vs metoclopramide) and hence does not interfere with the <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"8dfaeedbf91692777200561b2b1d2f\">therapeutic</span> effects of levodopa, but inhibits the D2 receptors on CTZ ➞ decreasing vomiting.</li>\n\t</ul>\n\t</li>\n\t<li><strong>Metoclopramide : 5 HT4 <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"7d8d28cda71692777180c89a3c86ce\">agonist</span> + D2 <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"2e432a4f3c1692777181e8e244ca0e\">antagonist</span> + raised Ach</strong>\n\t<ul>\n\t\t<li><strong>Crosses the blood-brain barrier</strong> and interferes with the <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"8dfaeedbf91692777200561b2b1d2f\">therapeutic</span> effects of levodopa, hence not preferred in levodopa-induced <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"998fb41ebc1692777202e46891c4a7\">vomiting</span> <strong>(Option A)</strong></li>\n\t\t<li>Causes <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"e2952dfc311692777187fa773bcc9f\">extrapyramidal</span> side effects.</li>\n\t</ul>\n\t</li>\n\t<li><strong>Antipsychotics :</strong>\n\t<ul>\n\t\t<li>Prochlorperazine<strong> (Option B)- DOC for violent vomiting</strong></li>\n\t\t<li>Chlorpromazine <strong>(Option C)</strong></li>\n\t</ul>\n\t</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<p> </p>",
