    {
      "text": "A 25-year-old female comes to the clinic with complaints of vomiting associated with her migraine headache for the past 2 days. Which of the following can be effective in this patient?",
      "choices": [
        {
          "id": 0,
          "text": "Lorazepam"
        },
        {
          "id": 1,
          "text": "Nabilone"
        },
        {
          "id": 2,
          "text": "Prochlorperazine"
        },
        {
          "id": 3,
          "text": "Dexamethasone"
        }
      ],
      "correct_choice_id": 2,
      "solution": "<p><strong>Correct answer: C) Prochlorperazine</strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>Explanation: </strong></p>\n\n<p>The drug of choice for migraine-induced <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"998fb41ebc1692777202e46891c4a7\">vomiting</span> is an <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"4123308aeb1692777181e8820312dd\">antipsychotic</span> such as <strong>prochlorperazine and chlorpromazine.</strong></p>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<p><strong>Antipsychotics :</strong></p>\n\n<ul>\n\t<li>They have <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"b934c33cc21692777181f55e558ff3\">antihistamine</span> and <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"9b4dbbb3321692777181e6fe172b88\">anticholinergic</span> properties and hence can be used in migraine-induced <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"9a8412e39e1692777193c550a5dbb4\">nausea</span> and vomiting.</li>\n\t<li>They <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"6b3de87b7c16927771901326efbcd2\">inhibit</span> D2 receptors in CTZ, which is the mechanism behind preventing <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"9a8412e39e1692777193c550a5dbb4\">nausea</span> and vomiting.</li>\n\t<li>They are also indicated in post-chemotherapy, <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"8f584900e71692777196a6e8943d4e\">postoperative</span> <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"9a8412e39e1692777193c550a5dbb4\">nausea</span> and <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"998fb41ebc1692777202e46891c4a7\">vomiting</span> and also in motion sickness.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<p><strong>Lorazepam (Option A): </strong>The sedative, <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"7607ee135116927771811ce8026ed0\">amnesic</span> and <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"82a86d431b1692777181cb3287b0ee\">anxiolytic</span> properties of <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"4398b2978c16927771915937fed503\">lorazepam</span> help be used as an <strong>anticipatory medication</strong> in patients with <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"16b76d1d1c1692777200240efcb0e2\">terminal</span> diseases.</p>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<p>Nabilone (<strong>Option B) </strong>which is a CB1 <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"9e4959f6f316927771978bb152d440\">receptor</span> agonist, is used prophylactically for <strong>post-chemotherapy-induced <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"9a8412e39e1692777193c550a5dbb4\">nausea</span> and vomiting.</strong></p>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<p>Dexamethasone <strong>(</strong><strong>Option D) </strong>(Corticosteroids) reduce <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"e747a47db616927771908bff4b8931\">inflammation</span> ➞ reduce the <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"9d21dd5d3116927771907405b181bc\">inflammatory</span> mediators like serotonin, dopamine, and substance P; mainly used in <strong>chemotherapy-induced <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"9a8412e39e1692777193c550a5dbb4\">nausea</span> and vomiting.</strong></p>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<p> </p>",
      "question_images": [],
      "explanation_video": null,
      "explanation_images": [],
      "explanation_audio_eng": "https://image.prepladder.com/content/22eThExEjKTnhyqKFbup1749195057.mp3",
      "explanation_audio_hin": "https://image.prepladder.com/content/N96UWzCi06IzifswcnvH1749195012.mp3"
    },
    {
      "text": "A 45-year-old female patient presents with mild to moderate pain in the upper right quadrant of her abdomen. Upon ultrasound examination, she is diagnosed with cholesterol gallstones. The physician prescribes ursodeoxycholic acid. Which of the following is the mechanism of action of this drug?",
      "choices": [
        {
          "id": 0,
          "text": "Decreases cholesterol absorption from the intestine"
        },
        {
          "id": 1,
          "text": "Decreases cholesterol synthesis in the liver"
        },
        {
          "id": 2,
          "text": "Increases cholesterol breakdown"
        },
        {
          "id": 3,
          "text": "Increases cholesterol uptake by adipocytes"
        }
      ],
      "correct_choice_id": 0,
      "solution": "<p><strong>Correct answer: A) Decreases cholesterol <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"5fcb9396d1169277718069dd7fa788\">absorption</span> from the intestine</strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>Explanation: </strong></p>\n\n<p>Ursodeoxycholic acid acts by decreasing cholesterol <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"5fcb9396d1169277718069dd7fa788\">absorption</span> from the intestine.</p>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<p style=\"text-align:center\"><img alt=\"\" data-author=\"\" data-hash=\"\" data-license=\"\" data-source=\"\" data-tags=\"\" height=\"492\" src=\"https://image.prepladder.com/content/qEON7xt1wghsLDBfJdi31724073563.jpg\" width=\"492\" /></p>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<ul>\n\t<li>Ursodeoxycholic acid is a naturally occurring <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"db283047011692777189a869dbce07\">hydrophilic</span> <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"cf978047b61692777183c0569f21f2\">bile</span> acid.</li>\n\t<li>When taken orally, it\n\t<ul>\n\t\t<li>Alters relative concentrations of <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"cf978047b61692777183c0569f21f2\">bile</span> acids by reducing its <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"5fcb9396d1169277718069dd7fa788\">absorption</span> from the intestine</li>\n\t\t<li>Decreases <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"7dd6eda7ce169277718325f22de9e8\">biliary</span> <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"a99114a6c216927771916f45ffc66c\">lipid</span> secretion</li>\n\t\t<li>Reduces cholesterol content in bile, making it less likely to <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"a1b06f401f1692777203a53393ba98\">form</span> gallstones</li>\n\t</ul>\n\t</li>\n\t<li>It is also <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"f86de533a11692777185301bc76ea5\">cytoprotective</span> in cholestatic liver diseases like <strong>primary <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"0aa16e71201692777198c4c07e2392\">sclerosing</span> cholangitis</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<p>Decreased cholesterol <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"3fda45538a1692777199ec2a5478a5\">synthesis</span> in the liver <strong>(Option B)</strong> is the mechanism of action of <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"891694e49616927771844bc996fbea\">chenodeoxycholic acid</span> and statins.</p>\n\n<p> </p>",
      "question_images": [],
      "explanation_video": null,
      "explanation_images": [
        "https://image.prepladder.com/content/qEON7xt1wghsLDBfJdi31724073563.jpg"
      ],
      "explanation_audio_eng": "https://image.prepladder.com/content/vR9p9YDWwSziZq2rDTGj1749198282.mp3",
      "explanation_audio_hin": "https://image.prepladder.com/content/EBkiff8AURAk4Buv8BVW1749198196.mp3"
    },
    {
      "text": "A 45-year-old female patient presents to the clinic with symptoms of severe malabsorption following an extensive intestinal resection due to Crohn's disease. She has been diagnosed with short bowel syndrome and is currently receiving parenteral nutrition.\n\nWhich of the following medications is not typically used to treat short bowel syndrome?",
      "choices": [
        {
          "id": 0,
          "text": "Growth hormone"
        },
        {
          "id": 1,
          "text": "Octreotide"
        },
        {
          "id": 2,
          "text": "Teduglutide"
        },
        {
          "id": 3,
          "text": "Ursodeoxycholic acid"
        }
      ],
      "correct_choice_id": 3,
      "solution": "<p><strong>Correct answer: D) Ursodeoxycholic acid</strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>Explanation:</strong></p>\n\n<p>Ursodeoxycholic acid is not used in short <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"37863e7aec169277718310f33c6a11\">bowel</span> syndrome but instead used in patients with <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"7dd6eda7ce169277718325f22de9e8\">biliary</span> colic symptoms.</p>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<p><strong>SHORT <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"37863e7aec169277718310f33c6a11\">BOWEL</span> SYNDROME :</strong></p>\n\n<ul>\n\t<li>Short <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"37863e7aec169277718310f33c6a11\">bowel</span> syndrome (SBS) is a difficult and frequently debilitating condition characterised by <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"819ebcc6691692777191f968d41a03\">malabsorption</span> and chronic diarrhoea. It occurs when a large portion of the <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"7840cca3ed16927771901d2f6cb32b\">intestine</span> is removed.</li>\n\t<li><strong>3 new drugs for the treatment of short <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"37863e7aec169277718310f33c6a11\">bowel</span> syndrome :</strong></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<p><strong>Growth hormone (Option A)</strong>: ➞ increases production of IGF-1 ➞ stimulates growth of <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"37863e7aec169277718310f33c6a11\">bowel</span> cells ➞ enhances nutrient absorption.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Octreotide (Option B): </strong>➞ decreases intestinal secretions ➞ decreases malabsorptive diarrhoea,</p>\n\n<p><strong>Teduglutide (Option D)</strong>: it is a <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"b566321fe8169277719716b1cf4df0\">recombinant</span> GLP2 <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"22e0051a181692777181872183edb2\">analogue</span> ➞ increases the production of IGF-1 ➞ stimulates gut epithelial proliferation.</p>\n\n<p> </p>",
      "question_images": [],
      "explanation_video": null,
      "explanation_images": [],
      "explanation_audio_eng": "https://image.prepladder.com/content/U9ygelx7LmmKiDyPRGen1749198427.mp3",
      "explanation_audio_hin": "https://image.prepladder.com/content/l7B9rS5jCtiKfnpHHuRr1749198356.mp3"
    },
    {
      "text": "A 45-year-old male presents to the clinic with complaints of chronic abdominal pain and significant weight loss over the past year. He reports frequent, bulky and foul-smelling stools. His medical history is significant for alcohol abuse over the past 20 years. Laboratory investigations reveal normal LFT, and imaging studies show calcifications in the pancreas. Considering the patient's clinical presentation and medical history, which of the following is the most appropriate treatment?",
      "choices": [
        {
          "id": 0,
          "text": "Lipase only"
        },
        {
          "id": 1,
          "text": "Amylase only"
        },
        {
          "id": 2,
          "text": "Lipase and trypsin"
        },
        {
          "id": 3,
          "text": "Proteinase and amylase"
        }
      ],
      "correct_choice_id": 2,
      "solution": "<p><strong>Correct answer: C) Lipase and trypsin</strong></p>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<p><strong>Explanation:</strong></p>\n\n<ul>\n\t<li>\n\t<p>In <strong>chronic pancreatitis</strong>, there is progressive loss of pancreatic <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"938890efd616927771870f4a611546\">exocrine</span> function affecting all three major enzymes — <strong>lipase</strong>, <strong>amylase</strong>, and <strong>proteases (trypsin)</strong>.</p>\n\t</li>\n\t<li>\n\t<p>Fat <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"819ebcc6691692777191f968d41a03\">malabsorption</span> is the most clinically significant due to <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"670caad03f16927771917b9f8e3c48\">lipase</span> deficiency, but protein <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"47d4bcce081692777186a1aafdde1a\">digestion</span> is also impaired due to <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"10c83adb331692777197f775bec1aa\">reduced</span> <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"fe13bbded1169277719694883c6ba4\">protease</span> (trypsin) secretion.</p>\n\t</li>\n\t<li>\n\t<p>Therefore, <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"0f160e4e42169277718771b715516a\">enzyme</span> replacement therapy should ideally include both <strong>lipase and <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"fe13bbded1169277719694883c6ba4\">protease</span> (trypsin)</strong> to address <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"819ebcc6691692777191f968d41a03\">malabsorption</span> of fats and proteins.</p>\n\t</li>\n\t<li>\n\t<p>Amylase supplementation is generally not needed, as carbohydrate <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"47d4bcce081692777186a1aafdde1a\">digestion</span> is less affected and often <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"fc497884941692777184bcca70ad8a\">compensated</span> by salivary <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"ee24d3aa0016927771810af81a9cf3\">amylase</span> and <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"da5d70d6c016927771839e073ce917\">brush border</span> enzymes.</p>\n\t</li>\n\t<li>\n\t<p>Hence, combined <strong>lipase and trypsin</strong> supplementation is more appropriate than <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"670caad03f16927771917b9f8e3c48\">lipase</span> alone.</p>\n\t</li>\n</ul>\n\n<table>\n\t<thead>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<th>Aspect</th>\n\t\t\t<th>Details</th>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t</thead>\n\t<tbody>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td>Clinical Presentation</td>\n\t\t\t<td>Chronic <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"1665a40f1016927771801899eaed5d\">abdominal</span> pain, steatorrhea, weight loss, pancreatic calcifications</td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td>Etiology</td>\n\t\t\t<td>Chronic alcohol abuse causing chronic pancreatitis</td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td>Enzyme Deficiency</td>\n\t\t\t<td>Lipase (fat digestion), proteases like <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"be1c04825c169277720006550a3ab2\">trypsin</span> (protein digestion)</td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td>Treatment</td>\n\t\t\t<td>Pancreatic <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"0f160e4e42169277718771b715516a\">enzyme</span> replacement therapy with <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"670caad03f16927771917b9f8e3c48\">lipase</span> and <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"fe13bbded1169277719694883c6ba4\">protease</span> (trypsin)</td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<p><strong>Lipase only (Option A):</strong> Incorrect because protein <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"47d4bcce081692777186a1aafdde1a\">digestion</span> <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"4885d5d0021692777189aac6dc80f7\">impairment</span> also contributes to malnutrition; <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"fe13bbded1169277719694883c6ba4\">protease</span> replacement improves overall <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"47d4bcce081692777186a1aafdde1a\">digestion</span> and nutrition.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Amylase only (Option B):</strong> Incorrect because carbohydrate <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"47d4bcce081692777186a1aafdde1a\">digestion</span> is usually preserved; <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"ee24d3aa0016927771810af81a9cf3\">amylase</span> replacement is unnecessary.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Proteinase and <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"ee24d3aa0016927771810af81a9cf3\">amylase</span> (Option D):</strong> Incorrect because <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"670caad03f16927771917b9f8e3c48\">lipase</span> replacement is critical for fat digestion; omission of <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"670caad03f16927771917b9f8e3c48\">lipase</span> would fail to treat steatorrhea.</p>\n\n<p> </p>",
